        FDA APPROVES HUMIRA FOR RHEUMATOID ARTHRITIS

The U.S. Food and Drug Administration has approved the drug
Humira, made by Abbott Labs, to treat moderate to severe
rheumatoid arthritis. Humira is the first human monoclonal
antibody approved for reducing symptoms and inhibiting the
progression of structural damage in adults with RA who have
not done well with other treatments. Humira is given every
other week through an injection and a specially designed
pre-filled syringe for RA patients whose hands might be
affected by crippling joint destruction will be available
in pharmacies next month. The FDA approved the drug after
reviewing the results of clinical trials on more than 2,000
RA patients. Some patients saw an improvement in RA signs
and symptoms as early as one week after taking the drug.
Humira can be prescribed alone or with other RA medications.
It resembles antibodies normally found in the body and works
by blocking tumor necrosis factor alpha, a protein that
plays a central role in the inflammatory responses of auto-
immune diseases such as RA.  


