            PROTECTION ORDERS WORK FOR WOMEN

Civil protection orders are effective at protecting women
from injuries inflicted by an abusive partner, a new study
indicates. "Based on these findings, civil protection
orders appear to be one of the few widely available inter-
ventions for victims of intimate partner violence that has
demonstrated effectiveness," says study author Victoria
Holt of the Department of Epidemiology at the University
of Washington in Seattle. The problem is only 20 percent
of the approximately 2 million U.S. women who are physical-
ly abused, stalked or raped by partners each year obtain
such orders, the study shows. The researchers say inter-
views of abused women show those who obtained and maintain-
ed a civil protection order were safer than those without
them in the five-month period after they were initially
threatened or abused. When Holt and colleagues interviewed
the women again four months later, they found the protec-
tion order effect had grown even stronger. 


