            COUNSELING HELPS HIGH RISK PATIENTS

A Department of Health and Human Services task force says
extended behavioral counseling can help patients who are at
high risk for heart disease and other chronic illnesses.
The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force noted, however,
there is not enough evidence to gauge the effectiveness of
brief, routine counseling among healthy adults. The task
force reviewed 35 years of diet counseling studies and con-
cluded intensive counseling by primary care physicians or
dietary specialists can help at-risk adult patients eat
less fat and more fruits and vegetables. Effective counsel-
ing typically involved multiple individual or group sessions
and stressed techniques to boost patients' skills, motiva-
tion, social supports and personal involvement in setting
goals. The task force cited a lack of controlled studies of
routine diet counseling in children and teens and a lack of
good information on the possible harms of diet counseling
as reasons for not recommending routine counseling for
those age groups.


